# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hashicorp-packer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] A **disk image** is a snapshot of a storage device's content – typically stored in a file on another storage device.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Traditionally, a disk image was relatively large because it was a bit-by-bit copy of every storage location of a device (i.e. every sector of a hard disk drive), but it is now common to only store allocated data to reduce storage space.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Compression and deduplication are commonly used to further reduce the size of image files.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk imaging is performed for a variety of purposes including digital forensics, cloud computing, system administration, backup, and emulation for digital preservation strategy.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Despite the benefits, storage costs can be high, management can be difficult and imaging can be time consuming.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk images can be made in a variety of formats depending on the purpose.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Virtual disk images (such as VHD and VMDK) are intended to be used for cloud computing, ISO images are intended to emulate optical media, such as a CD-ROM.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Raw disk images are used for forensic purposes.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Proprietary formats are typically used by disk imaging software.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk images were originally (in the late 1960s) used for backup and disk cloning of mainframe disk media.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Early ones were as small as 5 megabytes and as large as 330 megabytes, and the copy medium was magnetic tape, which ran as large as 200 megabytes per reel.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk images became much more popular when floppy disk media became popular, where replication or storage of an exact structure was necessary and efficient, especially in the case of copy protected floppy disks.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk image creation is called disk imaging and is often time consuming, even with a fast computer, because the entire disk must be copied.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Typically, disk imaging requires a third party disk imaging program or backup software.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] The software required varies according to the type of disk image that needs to be created.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] For example, RawWrite and WinImage create floppy disk image files for MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] In Unix or similar systems the dd program can be used to create raw disk images.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Apple Disk Copy can be used on Classic Mac OS and macOS systems to create and write disk image files.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Authoring software for CDs/DVDs such as Nero Burning ROM can generate and load disk images for optical media.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] A *virtual disk writer* or *virtual burner* is a computer program that emulates an actual disc authoring device such as a CD writer or DVD writer.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Instead of writing data to an actual disc, it creates a virtual disk image.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] A virtual burner, by definition, appears as a disc drive in the system with writing capabilities (as opposed to conventional disc authoring programs that can create virtual disk images), thus allowing software that can burn discs to create virtual discs.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Forensic imaging is the process of creating a bit-by-bit copy of the data on the drive, including files, metadata, volume information, filesystems and their structure.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Often, these images are also hashed to verify their integrity and that they have not been altered since being created.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Unlike disk imaging for other purposes, digital forensic applications take a bit-by-bit copy to ensure forensic soundness.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] The purposes of imaging the disk is to not only discover evidence preserved in digital information but also to examine the drive to gather clues of how the crime was committed.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Creating a virtual disk image of optical media or a hard disk drive is typically done to make the content available to one or more virtual machines.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Virtual machines emulate a CD/DVD drive by reading an ISO image.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] This can also be faster than reading from the physical optical medium.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Further, there are less issues with wear and tear.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] A hard disk drive or solid-state drive in a virtual machine is implemented as a disk image (i.e. either the VHD format used by Microsoft's Hyper-V, the VDI format used by Oracle Corporation's VirtualBox, the VMDK format used for VMware virtual machines, or the QCOW format used by QEMU).
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Virtual hard disk images tend to be stored as either a collection of files (where each one is typically 2GB in size), or as a single file.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Virtual machines treat the image set as a physical drive.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Educational institutions and businesses can often need to buy or replace computer systems in large numbers.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk imaging is commonly used to rapidly deploy the same configuration across workstations.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk imaging software is used to create an image of a completely-configured system (such an image is sometimes called a golden image).
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] This image is then written to a computer's hard disk (which is sometimes described as restoring an image).
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Image restoration can be done using network-based image deployment.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] This method uses a PXE server to boot an operating system over a computer network that contains the necessary components to image or restore storage media in a computer.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] This is usually used in conjunction with a DHCP server to automate the configuration of network parameters including IP addresses.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Multicasting, broadcasting or unicasting tend to be used to restore an image to many computers simultaneously.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] These approaches do not work well if one or more computers experience packet loss.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] As a result, some imaging solutions use the BitTorrent protocol to overcome this problem.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Network-based image deployment reduces the need to maintain and update individual systems manually.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Imaging is also easier than automated setup methods because an administrator does not need to have knowledge of the prior configuration to copy it.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] A disk image contains all files and data (i.e., file attributes and the file fragmentation state).
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] For this reason, it is also used for backing up optical media (CDs and DVDs, etc.), and allows the exact and efficient recovery after experimenting with modifications to a system or virtual machine.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Typically, disk imaging can be used to quickly restore an entire system to an operational state after a disaster.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Libraries and museums are typically required to archive and digitally preserve information without altering it in any manner.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Emulators frequently use disk images to emulate floppy disks that have been preserved.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] This is usually simpler to program than accessing a real floppy drive (particularly if the disks are in a format not supported by the host operating system), and allows a large library of software to be managed.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Emulation also allows existing disk images to be put into a usable form even though the data contained in the image is no longer readable without emulation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk imaging is time consuming, the space requirements are high and reading from them can be slower than reading from the disk directly because of a performance overhead.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Other limitations can be the lack of access to software required to read the contents of the image.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] For example, prior to Windows 8, third party software was required to mount disk images.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] When imaging multiple computers with only minor differences, much data is duplicated unnecessarily, wasting space.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Disk imaging can be slow, especially for older storage devices.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] A typical 4.7 GB DVD can take an average of 18 minutes to duplicate.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Floppy disks read and write much slower than hard disks.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Therefore, despite their small size, it can take several minutes to copy a single disk.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] In some cases, disk imaging can fail due to bad sectors or physical wear and tear on the source device.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] Unix utilities (such as dd) are not designed to cope with failures, causing the disk image creation process to fail.
[src:hashicorp-packer/disk-image] When data recovery is the end goal, it is instead recommended to use more specialised tools (such as ddrescue).
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] HashiCorp is headquartered in San Francisco, but its employees are distributed across the United States, Canada, Australia, India, and Europe.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] HashiCorp offers source-available libraries and other proprietary products.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] HashiCorp was founded in 2012 by Mitchell Hashimoto and Armon Dadgar, two classmates from the University of Washington's Paul G.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Allen School of Computer Science and Engineering .
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Co-founder Hashimoto was previously working on open-source software called Vagrant, which became incorporated into HashiCorp.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] On 29 November 2021, HashiCorp set terms for its IPO at $68-$72 at a valuation of $13 billion.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] HashiCorp considers its workers to be remote workers first rather than coming into an office on a full-time basis.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Around April 2021, a supply chain attack using code auditing tool codecov allowed hackers limited access to HashiCorp's customers networks.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] As a result, private credentials were leaked.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] HashiCorp revoked a private signing key and asked its customers to use a new rotated key.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Mitchell Hashimoto resigned from the company in December 2023.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] On April 24, 2024, the company announced it had entered into an agreement to be acquired by IBM for $6.4 billion, with the transaction expected to close by the end of the same year.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] This led to the Competition and Markets Authority of the United Kingdom launching an investigation into the acquisition in late 2024.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] The deal closed on February 27, 2025 for $6.4 billion after receiving the necessary regulatory approvals.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] HashiCorp provides a suite of tools intended to support the development and deployment of large-scale service-oriented software installations.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Each tool is aimed at specific stages in the life cycle of a software application, with a focus on automation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Many have a plugin-oriented architecture in order to provide integration with third-party technologies and services.
[src:hashicorp-packer/hashicorp] Additional proprietary features for some of these tools are offered commercially and are aimed at enterprise customers.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] This introduction describes Packer benefits and how you can get started with it.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] Packer is a community tool for creating identical machine images for multiple platforms from a single source configuration.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] Packer is lightweight, runs on every major operating system, and is highly performant, creating machine images for multiple platforms in parallel.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] Packer does not replace configuration management like Chef or Puppet.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] In fact, when building images, Packer is able to use tools like Chef or Puppet to install software onto the image.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] A *machine image* is a single static unit that contains a pre-configured operating system and installed software which is used to quickly create new running machines.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] Machine image formats change for each platform.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] Some examples include AMIs for EC2, VMDK and VMX files for VMware, and OVF exports for VirtualBox.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer-intro] For information about using HCP Packer to store metadata about build artifacts, refer to the HCP Packer documentation or sign into HCP to explore HCP Packer features.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer] Packer lets you create identical machine images for multiple platforms from a single source configuration.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer] A common use case is creating golden images for organizations to use in cloud infrastructure.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer] Use built-in and external plugins to perform tasks during each build.
[src:hashicorp-packer/packer] Manage images for your organization and extend Packer functionality.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] In computing, a **system image** is a serialized copy of the entire state of a computer system stored in some non-volatile form, such as a binary compressed file.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] If a system has all its state written to a disk (i.e. on a disk image), then a system image can be produced by copying the disk to a file elsewhere, often with disk cloning applications.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] A system is said to be capable of using system images if it can be shut down and later restored to exactly the same state.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] In such cases, system images can be used for backup.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Hibernation is an example that uses an image of the computer's entire RAM.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] A process image is a copy of a given process's state at a given point in time.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] It is often used to create persistence within an otherwise volatile system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] A common example is a database management system (DBMS).
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Most DBMS can store the state of its database or databases to a file before being closed down (see database dump).
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] The DBMS can then be restarted later with the information in the database intact and proceed as though the software had never stopped.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Another example would be the hibernate feature of many operating systems.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Here, the state of all RAM memory is stored to disk, the computer is brought into an energy saving mode, then later restored to normal operation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Some emulators provide a facility to save an image of the system being emulated.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] In video gaming this is often referred to as a savestate.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Another use is code mobility: a mobile agent can migrate between machines by having its state saved, then copying the data to another machine and restarting there.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Some programming languages provide a command to take a system image of a program.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] This is normally a standard feature in Smalltalk (inspired by FLEX) and Lisp, among other languages.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Development in these languages is often quite different from many other programming languages.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] For example, in Lisp the programmer may load packages or other code into a running Lisp implementation using the read-eval-print loop, which usually compiles the programs.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Data is loaded into the running Lisp system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] The programmer may then dump a system image, containing that pre-compiled and possibly customized code—and also all loaded application data.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Often this image is an executable, and can be run on other machines.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Similar, Lisp Machines were booted from Lisp images, called Worlds.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] The World contains the complete operating system, its applications and its data in a single file.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] It was also possible to save incremental Worlds, that contain only the changes from some base World.
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Before saving the World, the Lisp Machine operating system could optimize the contents of memory (better memory layout, compacting data structures, sorting data, ...).
[src:hashicorp-packer/system-image] Although its purpose is different, a "system image" is often similar in structure to a core dump.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:hashicorp-packer/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
